<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Xylococcus</i> <i>bicolor</i> is dominant or co-dominant with <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> in the shrub canopy with <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>crassifolius</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>tomentosus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>verrucosus</i>, <i>Cneoridium</i> <i>dumosum</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Heteromeles</i> <i>arbutifolia</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>berberidifolia</i>, <i>Rhamnus</i> <i>ilicifolia</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>integrifolia</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>ovata</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>apiana</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and <i>Xylococcus bicolor</i> average 10-30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Gordon and White 1994).</li>
		
		<li><i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and <i>Xylococcus bicolor</i> have 30-60% relative cover, though sometimes <i>X. bicolor</i> is less important in cover as a sub-dominant with > 1% absolute cover (Evens and San 2005, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Xylococcus bicolor</i> > 50% relative cover of the shrub canopy (Dixon et al. 2019).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Lower to upper slopes of all aspects. Soils are shallow and sandy.  </div>
</div>

        
