<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Xylococcus bicolor </i>is an erect evergreen shrub that grows 2.5 m tall. Shrubs have well-developed lignotubers. Seeds collect in a seed bank as stones of fused seeds (Hickman 1993). The coastal distribution of <i>X. bicolor </i>suggests it is frost sensitive. <br/>
<br/>
Previously this alliance was published in the 2009 book as the  <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum - Xylococcus bicolor</i> Shrubland Alliance.  Additional surveys have demonstrated that <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i> is not always present or co-dominant.  <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>is a long-lived, shade-intolerant shrub that grows to 3.5 m. Shrubs produce dimorphic seeds after 3 years of age. Some seeds are dormant, whereas others readily germinate, though viability is low. Seeds disperse during the summer near the parent plant, and seedlings may emerge during the next rainy season. Dormant seeds accumulate in the soil and are not subject to heavy predation. <i>A. fasciculatum </i>rejuvenates between fires by continually producing new sprouts from a semi-buried lignotuber (McMurray 1990a). <br/>
<br/>
Gordon and White (1994) was the first to recognize this localized alliance in the lower elevation chaparral of the Peninsular Range foothills, which they recognized as <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum-Xylococcus bicolor-Ceanothus tomentosus </i>series. Since then, Evens and San (2005) inventoried this vegetation elsewhere in San Diego Co., and Klein and Evens (2005) found it in western Riverside Co., where it is common and particularly variable. <br/>
<br/>
Holland (1986) considered localized stands with <i>Arctostaphylos glandulosa </i>ssp. <i>crassifolia </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant), <i>Comarostaphylis diversifolia </i>ssp. <i>diversifolia </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant), <i>Ceanothus verrucosus </i>(a CNPS list 2.2 plant), and <i>Quercus dumosa </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) to be indicative of southern maritime chaparral (see discussion of southern maritime chaparral in the Changes Since the First Edition section). Hogan et al. (1996) considered the more coastal stands with these rare plants to be members of the <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum - Salvia mellifera </i>alliance, and placed the more inland stands in this alliance. Evens and San (2005) inventoried similar stands in central San Diego Co., and Klein and Evens (2005) described <i>Arctostaphylos rainbowensis </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) in western Riverside Co. as belonging to this alliance with <i>X. bicolor</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
