<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>and <i>Xylococcus bicolor </i>are adapted to low- to moderate-intensity fire, and they typically respond by sprouting. For <i>A. fasciculatum, </i>heat and charcoal stimulate seed germination from its seed bank during the first rainy season after a fire with low to moderate recruitment. Surviving adventitious buds vigorously sprout from the lignotuber following disturbances such as fire or cutting (McMurray 1990a). For <i>X. bicolor, </i>seeds germinate after a fire but rarely establish. Top-killed plants sprout from the lignotuber after aboveground portions after the fire. Shrub cover regains pre-burn cover levels as the shrubs age.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
