    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bh-j). Stands constitute several associations on a wide variety of substrates (CVIS 1995, Evens and San 2005). One stand has been sampled on Santa Catalina Island (Dixon et al. 2019) and it is likely that this alliance occurs on other southern Channel Islands. Stands also occur at Torrey Pines State Reserve adjacent to some <i>Pinus torreyana</i> stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bf, Bn). Stands occur in the Santa Ana Mountains (Klein and Evens 2005), and central and western San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005, Gordon and White 1994) on soils derived from granite, though some occur on gabbro.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Intense or very frequent burning regimes will eliminate shrubs, such as <i>Xylococcus bicolor.</i> Fire intervals under 10 years will favor annuals and coastal scrub species (Gordon and White 1994). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
